We all know what to expect when you get Dominos. It's not going to be the best pizza you ever had, but they are open late and its convenient. The staff at this location were especially courteous and friendly even with my late night order. However, someone needs to address the terrible answering system. I called and could barely make out what the recorded message was saying. Muffled, garbled, almost impossible to understand. I just pushed buttons until someone answered, and once a human was on the other end of the line, sound quality was perfect, so it wasn't my phone, wasn't the connection and it wasn't my ears, it's the terrible answering system. Fix that issue and this was a 5 star experience.

We had a wonderful stay here in the spa suites. The staff was very accommodating and helpful. The road closures and avalanche warnings forced us to cancel a lot of our excursions so we spent a lot of time here. The spa was great, sauna was very nice to use, and a full breakfast was a great option in the morning. You're close enough to town to walk everywhere, but they also offer a shuttle. Pro staff, nice amenities, and a beautiful spot. We'd love to come back in the summer and stay creekside.

This is the 3rd time I have rated them. I have had some great experiences and some horrible ones at our Casper location. But I am changing them from a 1 to a 5 star since they have earned it back with our last 4 experiences with them.  The dine in restaurant has raised to a level in the past few months we haven't seen here in 5 years. The service is exceptional and the food is back to what we have grown to expect from them in the last 30 years. With that said, their take away is absolutely phenomenal... The food has always been as good at home as it is off the line.  Hot, but not burnt from the lights or heated in some other artificial way.  The salad is crisp and fresh and the bread sticks almost as good as right out of the oven. In the last month we have done take away twice and dined in once and all three have been better then the one before.  My hat is off to either the new manager or the change the old one has made whichever is the case.  The last visit was my birthday lunch and I enjoyed every minute of it from our server to the food to the wonderful desert they gave me to the great plate of chocolate with "Happy Birthday" on it.  I highly recommend this Olive Garden, not only over their other locations but over 95% of all restaurants in town.

We arrived on a Tuesday evening and there was a 45 minute wait and took that long to get a table. The placed was packed and I am always hesitant at trying a new steak place. We ordered the cowboy steak for 2 and the 3/$15 sides (truffle mac and cheese, truffle asparagus, and brussel sprouts). I thought for the amount of food you get for your sides was a good deal. There was not much truffle taste in the asparagus, but you could definitely taste a hint of it. Those were my least favorite side dish, but it was still good. The truffle mac and cheese was my favorite side. Great truffle flavor and crispy on the top and bottom. No complaints there! We ordered medium rare for our steak and it was cooked perfectly. Flavor was on point! I was not expecting that at all. The server was nice and the food took a little time, but it was busy, so it was expected. Atmosphere was dark and dimly lit, but fit the ambiance. It was loud it there, but that did not bother either of us. Overall, it was a good experience and prices were fair for what you got! I would definitely give it a try if you are willing to wait.

Absolutely amazing Mexican restaurant! I've tried to get my fix many times across SD, WY & MT with no success. Most restaurants are bland and boring, with much of their food tasting like it was out of a can. That is NOT the case with Frida's. Everything was incredibly fresh. The tortillas, salsa, hot sauce... all homemade. The restaurant itself was exceptionally clean. The bathroom smelled like a pool (in a good, properly sanitized kinda way) and tables were cleaned within two minutes of other guests' departure. My server was incredibly attentive to my needs and checked in frequently. If only there was a location in Rapid City, I would be there weekly. With a two hour drive, I would still consider making a trip every couple of months just to eat here. Do us all a favor and support this establishment. We need amazing places like this to stick around out here on the prairie.

Long time Subaru enthusiast, owned a 2011 WRX for years before I purchased a 2018 Subaru STI from the Subaru in Casper.  About 3-4 months ago I cracked my bumper and had it replaced with a brand new bumper/paint.

Move to Cheyenne a week ago, first time bringing my car in for a simple oil change.  I’m asked if I’d like a complimentary car wash, which I regrettably accepted.

I receive my car and notice there’s a large chip in the paint of my bumper.  Keep in mind the vehicle has 15K miles and the bumper probably less than 3K.

I call the dealership and am transferred to the “manager” Mike.  He doesn’t answer, so I leave a voicemail politely explaining the situation and requesting a call back.

I wait two hours and still, no response.  At this point, I drive back to the dealership to wait an additional 15 minutes so they can track him down because no one seems to know where he is.

Immediately he begins to defend the fact that it’s not possible his car washers, using bristle brushes, could’ve knicked or caused any damage.  THEN, he pulls out a report that allegedly was filled out when my car was worked on, which was not at all the report that was given to me when I first left.

Their inspection for my car came back perfect, absolutely nothing wrong.  Then, when I’m asking about the chip in the paint, he finds a “paper that was on his desk” describing previous marks on a brand new bumper and further attempts to tell me I need to go BACK to the Subaru in CASPER to “look into clear coat warranty”

I’m absolutely appalled that a manager would choose to lose a customer who has spent thousands of dollars across several dealerships, driving a brand new Subaru STI with warranty (basically their ‘prime’ customer type) over a paint chip.

I couldn’t say nicer things about the girls at the reception desk!  Unfortunately they aren’t the ones who can make things right though.  Hopefully this review deters even one Subaru enthusiast from losing their love for the brand due to a poor manager.

As you can see from the photos, that’s not at all “road debris” especially 30 minutes after receiving from them.   Absolutely falls on the management that fails to take accountability.  Instead I will take these photos to Small Claims Court, or wherever necessary to make this right.  To try to blame this on another Subaru dealership is pathetic.

Vegan and Vegetarian friendly.

I've been her for breakfast and lunch several times.  They make a good omelet and have coffee good enough to drink black.  There always are interesting  pastries.  My favorite is their Apple Strudel. I've never had better anywhere else.  Same is true for their Orange Cranberry Bread Pudding.  Their stuffed French Toast was so good I enjoyed it without adding any butter or syrup.  It's a ginormous portion which is enough for two to enjoy so either bring a friend or a really big appetite.  I brought half home to enjoy later.

Another time I went there for lunch. I had a in house made vegan burger called "Veggie Treat" which is made from garbanzo beans and other veggies, and is served with a side of fries, or fruit salad, or salad bar (I chose the salad bar). I also had a pastry called a "Bamba" and coffee good enough to drink black. My guest had the "Hub Burger".

They cooked both of our burgers on the same grill but have a section of it reserved for non-meat cooking.

Presently they are open for breakfast and lunch.  They have a wide assortment of fresh made pastries prepared in their own kitchen.  They are a welcome addition to downtown daytime dining in Cheyenne.

I have had meals at very expensive steakhouses ($100 +) and I would take this any day over that. Even if money was no object! Firewater’s price was reasonable too and if anything, it felt as if I was getting more for my money. If your in Saratoga this should be a mandatory stop for anyone looking for well priced, delicious food!

An experience all unto itself, Little America is an historic bit of motoring Americana; a nicely-kept, relaxing hotel, diner, playground, gas station, and gift shop out in the wide-open of Wyoming along Interstate 80.  Stop in and fill up your tank, fill up your stomach, snag a gift or a bit of road trip memorabilia, or check in for a good night's sleep.  The place has been here since 1934, and continues to offer motorists a nice respite from the road.  No, it's not The Ritz, but there is no Ritz within 500 miles, and there's plenty to enjoy right here.

Very very very cute ranch. It is about 30-45 mins outside of the east entrance of Yellowstone. A little hard to see the board at night because it is black. You turn in and there is a Creek right there. The ranch is on the left and a trail on the right. We got there around 10 pm at night and could not find the main cabin. The owner, however, was up in her cabin and saw us come and graciously directed us to our cabin. Extremely cute cabin. We had chose the one with a double bed and two single beds - sitting bull. That's two separate rooms which connect through the bathroom. It's all wooden so things creak. But totally loved it!! We stayed for 2 nights and requested a campfire the second night and they started one for us. We bought the s'mores. It is very homely, which I loved. A lot of the people staying there seem to come here very often. I could not distinguish between customers and family!

They offer breakfast for 10.95 per person. It's is very filling. Loved the hash browns and the eggs. We didn't take the horse rides and fishing trips they offer, but may be worth a shot. Good place to stay at if you are coming from Cody.

Not much to do in east Yellowstone so if you want to go to the main park, this is not the best accommodation option.

Snake River was exactly what we needed after a Long Unexpected Day of Driving.
We arrived in Jackson at 9p rather than 6p, so there weren’t many options left open. The good news is SRB stays open til 11p, and serve until at least 9:30p.

We split a whole Caesar, a cup of chowder, the bolognese, and the burger.

They were all wonderful. I loved the Ragu in the pasta, and the noodles were perfect. The dish had a nice light flavor - not huge tomato sauce flavor, or just buttered noodles. The burger was super flavorful, with some awesome bacon. The chowder was really thick and sweet, and the salad crisp and zesty.

Can’t speak to the beers but they have fun names.

Best of all, the bar is huge, comfy, well lit, not too loud, with the nicest staff we could hope for. Super attentive and helpful and friendly.

Thanks for saving our dinner and our night.

Who knew that the best massaman curry our little taste buds have ever had the privilege of savoring would be found in the middle of Wyoming. It was beyond compare. So good my husband ordered another dish to go.

We usually order the same two dishes any Thai place we go. Pad thai and massaman curry. The pad thai was good but it wasn't anything to write home about. The helpings were very generous and so good. Despite having only one server we actually were given our food fairly quickly.

The staff was just the perfect amount of friendly and helpful although clearly they needed more help to attend to the constant stream of people frequenting the place.

Would definitely return. I would have given it two thumbs up but they were too busy shoveling food into my face.

Ps. Bathrooms were small and I doubt someone handicap could maneuver into it. But maybe the other one was better?

Oh and I almost forgot the best part, the massaman curry comes with a slice of avocado. Taste. Buds. Blown.

Well, I needed some smoked meat and Boomer's is right up the road from my hotel.  I walked in and the place was empty.  Bad sign I wondered?  I went with my hungry gut and ordered some pulled pork, ribs, potato salad and coleslaw to go.  The smell of the food tantalized me all the way to my room.  I broke open the to go containers and to my amazement, I found some good looking barbecue.  The ribs fall off the bone and have nice flavor, although they could use a bit more smoke flavor for my taste.  The pulled pork is yummy and goes wonderfully with the sauce they have, which is perfect.  The potato salad is quite good.  The coleslaw is not going to be to everyone's taste, but it sure hit my tastebuds on the nose!  It's vinegar based and kind of purple.  I'd recommend this place for sure.

Snake River Brewing gets pretty decent reviews, but it just wasn’t hitting for us. When we pulled up, there’s a large, outdoor space with a bunch of seating, green space, etc. - it looks super fun actually! It was raining and cold the day we were there so we sat inside which was fine by us. Cozied up at a table right next to the fireplace and that’s where their 3 stars are coming from. Fire was great, however, there were a bunch of flies near our table and upon further inspection, all around the fireplace, windows, etc. was dirty; spiderwebs, dust & dirt. I know this is a brewery therefore you’ll have the smell of beer throughout, but the smell was like stale beer that had been sitting for a while - just not appealing.

The food:
Apparently they’re known for their chili and it’s won awards - it’s a beef/bison chili - it was good, but not great. The chili on its own that is - with all of the toppings, this helped elevate the flavors a bit. Overall, I’d rate the chili a 7.

The beer:
I opted for their sour - again, good but not anything to write home about. Would give that a 6.5.

The service:
Was average - I’d give it a 7.

The COVID:
Staff wears masks and gloves - hand sanitizer can be found throughout, so they’re doing what they should be doing in that respect. An 8.

The overall:
A good place to grab a couple of beers and hang with friends - they also have plenty of TV’s if you want to catch a game. The cleanliness is really what made this review a 3 - if it weren’t for that, would have probably rated it a 4, but nothing was outstanding and nothing was horrible.

Locals clearly eat here too. I went with breakfast for dinner. Portions are normal to small-very reasonable in our super sized world-but not large. We were there with another family of 4 and the waitress handled our total party of 4 kids 4 adults just fine. Sandwiches were okay but the shrimp and fries were surprisingly good in landlocked Wyoming-generous serving and fried just right. This place also has a huge pie selection but the waitress did not even ask if we wanted dessert.

We ended up buying a peach pie on the return trip home and ate it elsewhere! It was tasty.

Overall, not bad, not great, but a good pit stop on the way to Mt. Rushmore.

Stopped in Sheridan WY. Tried the Cowboy Cafe. Loved it. It was a beautiful day so I sat outside. The portions were a nice size and leaned towards being generous. Had the bacon wrapped meatloaf, chefs salad and a slice of raspberry peach pie. The meatloaf had a much smoother texture and different seasonings than I'm used to but I enjoyed it. It also came with simple, but good mashed potatoes and steamed veggies that stole the show. I could have eaten a whole plate of them! The chefs salad was good. It had quite a bit of meat. I liked that it had roast beef in it. Last, but not least was the pie. They probably had 8-10 pies to choose from. The peach in the peach raspberry pie toned down the intense flavor of the raspberries a little bit. All in all it was a very good meal. After dinner I walked up and down the street. It is the origional downtown which Is very quaint. It was like walking through a gallery as there were amazing bronze statues every few feet lining both sides of the street. Lovely. l am definitely looking foward going back the the Cowboy Cafe and strolling along the streets of Sheridan, WY.

Room was very large, with a full-size couch and easy chair in the main room, as well as a dining-room table.  Up a couple steps and around the corner, there is a kitchen with a good-sized frig, a half-stove with two burners, microwave, and coffee maker.  The frig was stocked with breakfast needs such as bagels & cream cheese, orange juice, and other continental breakfast-type items, so that we could take breakfast whenever we wanted it without leaving the room.  Coffee and creamers were also provided.
The room seemed more like an apartment than a typical hotel room, and was a place we'd definitely recommend to others, especially if you are about to go into the East entrance to Yellowstone!

CONS:  A little far from the town of Cody, so it's best to stop for gas and other supplies on your way in.  Restaurant wasn't open when we were there, so I can't really comment on that.  Our room was downstairs and the window was near the road.  It didn't bother us, but it was possible to hear traffic going by - what there was of it!

Horrible flaw in cabins.The cabins that face each other have high ceilings, with high windows, but those windows have no curtains.

If, as happened with us, your neighbor leaves on their porch light, which is only controlled from within the cabin, then get ready for your entire cabin to have an ultra bright light lighting up your entire room all night.

And get ready to have the front house staff cover and say anything to get you use to the fact that they will not do anything about it. We were first told, "we'll give them call". 30 mins and nothing changed, we called again and were told "we'll call them again". One hour later and again no changed, we called a third time. This time we were told "they never answered, and even if they did, we can't make someone turn of their porch light. Just throw some of your pillows up to block the windows". Im sorry what? So this entire time you made it sound like something was being done, but actually you never talked to anyone? You can't send someone to knock? Instead throw some pillows up to the windows 12 feet up?  Why would you give the only control to an outside light to the user inside, and not give the cabin across the way curtains? All this for $400+ a night because of flaw in your cabin architecture? Give me a break.

We decided we wanted to cut our stay short and end our vacation early because our room was so lite up that neither myself, my wife or my 3 year old couldn't sleep. They told us sorry but there are no refunds.

Thought I was treating my family to a nice higher end location. Instead i got one of the worse, overpriced stays of my life. The cabin setup, those answers, and lack of front desk...I'll never stay here again. Save the money on this over priced place and stay somewhere else in town.

Only redeeming factor was the cleaning staff, they were great and always helpful. That was part of the reason I also hated the front desks idea of throwing pillows up top. The cleaning staff will have to work harder to retrieve them. It showed a lack of respect for the cleaning staff and laziness of the front desk. Instead just send someone to knock. Come on.

As a former line cook of this restaurant I would highly advise you to take your business elsewhere in town. Not only have the former employees gone unpaid for their labor (including Valentines day, which is one of the busiest days in the business year for Cody), there are major health concerns within the kitchen in this establishment.
I've worked within kitchens in Downtown Seattle, Denver, South Carolina, New Orleans, and multiple restaurants in Cody and I've never encountered such a concerning kitchen. Upon hiring I came into a completely unsanitized environment. The fryer hadn't been cleaned in months. From the looks of it it could have been years since the actual equipment had been cleaned, I've attached a photo. I have never seen kitchen equipment covered in this much grease. It took an entire shift of two employees scraping the caked on grit. The establishment doesn't own a oil basin so there is no way to dispose of the used fryer oil and as a result it is very rarely cleaned. Usually it's required to at least drain and sift the oil nightly, and clean the fryer itself weekly, and during my five months of employment it was cleaned once. My concerns were brought to the owner with little attention on his part.
The knives which are used to cut raw meat along with raw vegetables on the same board were never sanitized between uses and sat overnight filthy and reused again the next day. Along with the water pot used to reboil the precooked pasta, the water would sit in the pot for days reused and rarely drained. The baskets which hold the pasta were never cleaned.
The walk-in refrigerator is outdated and contains a dark mold that covers the wooden shelves which could very well be black mold. It is nearly never cleaned or shown any attention. Rotting food sits in the corners. In one case of being cleaned, when we tried to lift the pallets off the floor to mop, there was so much gunk underneath that it actually ripped the floor tile off completely because it was stuck to the pallet.
As to the quality of the ingredients, it's laughable that this restaurant can claim fine dining. The sauce comes out of a can, and the meat is the lowest quality the owner can find, along with all the other ingredients. The establishment claims it has the best steaks in town, yet they don't own a grill. To try to compete with the many steak houses on main street it is asinine to claim themselves as a steakhouse. Most of the steaks will sit thawed for weeks during the winter before being served.
The owner was absent for almost the entirety of my employment. He would not communicate with his employees and shown no concern to the state of his establishment. In fact when he came back, I watched him prepare a meal grabbing a raw chicken breast with his bare hands and continue to prep and serve. On Valentine's day, he had a seven year old child preparing raw salads for the public, with no gloves (since they obviously don't make a size small enough for children).
It's concerning that nearly all of the five star reviews are from either his employees, or his business friends. This restaurant may fool the tourists, but when it comes to the community of Cody, it is easily defined as one of the worst establishments in town.

They get two stars ONLY for the amazing view of wildlife.
Our server admittedly knew nothing about sourcing of menu items, which surprised me since Mammoth Dining Room touts their "4 Star Green Restaurant Certification" so proudly.
We started with the "Smoked Lake Trout Plate". We ordered this because we know Lake Trout is an invasive species, and we like to support vendors that try to eradicate invasive species.
Here is the problem, the menu states the lake trout is "farm raised". I could not help but laugh because any angler knows that Lake Trout aka Mackinaw are deep water fish that are impossible to "farm". I found out that they source the fish from "Native Fish Keepers"
from the Flathead Lake in NW Montana.
I pulled up the website and asked to speak to the chef. I showed him that the website clearly says "wild-caught", and asked why the menu says "farm raised". His response was, "wow, I didn't know it was wild caught, and I also didn't know the menu said farm raised". I explained why this minor detail mattered, but he didn't seem to care very much. I emailed Chef Mike Dean that evening to address this error. Chef Dean was clearly too busy to respond.
While this may seem like a minor detail, it is not. It exemplifies the credibility of a location, the staff, and moreover, the corporation. I stopped in two weeks after I brought this to the attention of Chef Alex, and Chef Dean, and the menu STILL says farm raised, despite them admitting the error.
After our "farm raised lake trout" plate 🤣 we had a Bison Tenderloin, ordered medium rare, presented to us at medium well. I'm curious now if that was Bison or if it was in fact a cattle yard cow?

What can I say, a little bit of a let down for this highly touted establishment. The food was good and definitely worth the often 30+ minute wait. What brings this restaurant down is the inhospitable host staff, and lack of sanitary care during this COVID-19 time of heightened cleanliness.

The hostess went to seat us and had to have us wait as she bussed the area around where we were to be seated. After sitting down a little while later a busser comes by and comments about the large number of tortilla chips all over the floor where we are sitting and how we have not even been served food yet. He seemed quite embarrassed.

As we were eating we kept seeing what appeared to be personal items and dishes commingled behind a ledge where the stuffed animals are displayed. Upon closer look there was all sorts of debris and other junk up there, it certainly did not look like a safe and sanitary way to store plates and silverware.

The drinks were left mostly empty and the service remained lackluster. All in all, really a bit disappointed in this storied establishment.

Bought higher end leather Flex-steel furniture (sofa/love-seat/recliner - $6500) from Farnham’s mid-February 2020.  Delivery was prompt & courteous.  After about a year noticed foam padding in arms was breaking down.  Contacted management & informed them of problem and stated that we would like to file a warranty claim. Asked if they would send someone to look at defects (January) and they said due to Covid pandemic please send photos.  I sent photos & copy of invoice.  They said it was easier to replace the arms rather than repair them.  After a month, I contacted them & was told the parts hadn’t come yet & could take longer due to Covid delays.  Called in April & was told the parts came in but now they are waiting on upholstery guy to get back to them to schedule repairs.  Really disappointed in being slow played!!!  I’m beginning to think they are not going to warranty their products.  I’m less than impressed with their warranty service.

05/10/21 -update
Finally getting some movement on getting this resolved.  Updating stars to three stars since they have sent repair person.  Recliner has been returned & they are working on sofa.  Still not overly impressed with communication from Farnham’s management!

To summarize my 2 star review: we got to eat one dish out of 4 that we ordered and it was delicious and the ambiance was really cool. The rest of the experience was NOT.

I consider myself a foody and was really excited to come to this restaurant. They were closed Sunday/Monday so we had it on our list to come on Tuesday..
Boy where we disappointed.

We got to the restaurant at 530 (when they opened) and we were sat immediately. We  didn’t get our first order (noodles) until 630 PM.

We spoke to another server who was a nice blonde lady and she apologized and comped us a free round of drinks. We appreciated this as we were hungry and still waiting for our food at this point....

Our server FINALLY drops our noodles an hour and 20 minutes later and said it would be another 25 minutes for the curry we ordered.... to be clear this is a two person table!!! We ordered noodles, curry, nan and broccoli.

We asked to take our food to go because we had been sitting there for an hour and a half. When we FINALLY get the rest of our to go order at 645... our server didn’t even order the broccoli!

We waited an hour and 45 minutes - got to eat one dish in the restaurant ( to their credit it was really good) requested the rest to go because of how long it took & then didn’t even get our full order Togo.

Our server said that they were busy with to go orders..... I have worked in a restaurant as a server for over 7 years and this was the worst experience I have had. If the kitchen is prioritizing to go orders rather than taking care of their customers in the restaurant that is a problem. If our server was not communicating with the kitchen/management team - then he was just not doing his job and the management team needs to better train their staff.

I only give reviews when I have a wonderful experience or a terrible experience. The ONE dish we had was good, but I wouldn’t waste my time coming back here due to the service.

I hope management reads this review and looks at the way your managing your business. Cut to go orders if your kitchen is swamped and prioritize your current customers.

The atmosphere is charming-- fresh flowers, pretty glassware, and clean linens. The new elements of carpentry lend the space a more natural, airy appearance. The menus are professionally printed on paper (perhaps an indication that the menu updates will be seasonal and comprised of more than white-out over the former price).

The staff are dashing in black pants, white button-downs, and small aprons and their courtesy, timing, and grace is uncommon in towns like ours. They know just how long to linger for a chat, when to refill drinks, and when to bring the next course.

The food is excellently prepared with a focus on flavor. The combinations of herbs and spices and the parings of proteins, grains, and vegetables are indicative of an experienced, knowledgeable chef. The desserts are also expertly considered. The homemade mint ice-cream tastes likely a freshly picked sprig.

You won’t find a more welcoming atmosphere in town and you certainly won’t taste anything more delicious than the options at Eve’s.

Twilight zone entrance. Went in at about 11:20 am for breakfast. Looked like a cute place to try. Two waitresses kept going by but nobody stopped. Another couple walks in and about 5 minutes later she waits on them. About 20 minutes into it we get asked if we've been waited on. Ordered a coffee each. Waitress comes back with one. Fine ok I guess I drink water. Then let's order breakfast....oh we stopped serving breakfast about 40 minutes ago. Then we need a few more minutes to decide.  Comes back one orders a sandwich, I order just a simple side salad with a side of French. Waitress comes with food sits it down, well guess it's Italian or none so I start eating my lettuce, slice of tomato and cucumber slice. Oh my goodness they gave me lettuce that was old and wilted and tasted awful. I give up. I told the waitress it's been non-stop wrong since I stepped in.  I wish you all luck if you try it but this woman will not return for a second chance.

Stopped at Sanford's for a late lunch while visiting my nephew in Sheridan and it was outstanding we ended up having only a couple of appetizers off there extensive menu because it was so late and we were having going to be having a big dinner at home later. But these 2 appetizers could have been meals by themselves we ordered without asking a full loaf of onion strings and a half order of nachos what a surprise when they were brought out the onion strings on a platter and the nachos in an iron skillet and they both looked incredible. There was only 2 of us but these appetizers could have easily fed 4 people. My nephew and I tried our best but didn't come close to finishing. Both of these appetizers were wonderful the onion strings were perfectly deep fried with a light and very tasty coating that we couldn't quite figure out and they came with an excellent dipping sauce. The nachos were tremendous they were served in the skillet there made in and they are loaded with your choice of chicken or beef we chose beef and than they pile on the cheese and onions and beans and sour cream,tomatoes and we think a bit of avocado and tortilla chips all layered and incredibly delicious. The service was great and inside of this bar/restaurant is such a good time to see this is a must do if your in Sheridan.

As someone that travels frequently places like this are a Godsend. I honestly believe it would be in the top two if not the best Thai in New Orleans.  Thai places are kinda special. I have not been to Thailand so if you are native and come here and are disappointed I'm sorry.

I had the shrimp omlette and had no expectations of it being good. It's Wyoming for Pete's sake. Boy was I shocked. I mean really this place knocked it out the park. I had the Larb salad to go and it is probably the best I've ever had. Back to that omelette. Of course the shrimp are/were frozen. That's how the world works. FYI 90% of the shrimp you eat on the Gulf Coast are frozen. I own a shrimp boat. Don't tell me the "oh I get them off the boat yada yada" This omelette would be in a rotation of places I would go back home.

I can't comment on the buffet. I didn't have it.

I would like to add. This place is as good as any James Beard restaurants that I frequent in Nola. Seriously. This place could be a contender for a James Beard award. I mean that.

The hostess was very frazzled and visibly upset when we arrived. She found us an open table after frantically running around to find an open seat. We would have never known otherwise because we only waited less than 5 minutes.
It took our server (Taylor) a bit to get to us, but once she did, she took great care of us! She never hesitated to fill drinks or ask how things were going. She chatted with us in her down time and was very friendly. I ordered the Noodles. There flavor was a bit overwhelming. The sauce seems like someone had dumped a ton of soy sauce all over the plate. My husband ordered the bacon burger with regular fries. The ranch he requested was some of the BEST we've ever had! He loved the flavor of the seasoned fries and the burger was cooked perfect. We ordered the spicy tomato bisque and grilled cheese that didn't make it out until after our entrees were at the table.tl That didn't bug us one bit, the flavor of the bisque was more than we ever expected. I've had authentic french tomato bisque and this made the traditional bisque seem bland in comparison. The grill cheese was perfectly grilled and cheese was melted immaculately.  We ordered the s'mores desert that was very good. The chocolate ice cream was very rich and full of flavor. The marshmallow however seemed as though it came from a jar. It tasted of stale confectionery sugar. I should have gone for the peach cobbler. When it came time to pay we found it difficult as we never keep cash or cards on us. I tried to pay using Google pay, but they didn't accept any kind of digital payment. We figured it out, but it was inconvenient. We were given a 10% off coupon to Provisions next door. Unfortunately we are in recovery, we can gift it though. Taylor was great! Give her a raise 😄

Over all we had a great experience and would highly recommend this dining experience to all of your friends!

An old cowboy-style chuckwagon supper followed by almost two hours of Western entertainment. This place is all about family; in a way you can't find many other places. The Wranglers and their family run the ticket booths you pass through on your way in, they serve you the supper you eat, and then they entertain you with wholesome family entertainment til sundown.
The food isn't stellar (3/5), but it's meant to pay homage to the foods a Cowboy would get from a chuckwagon while driving cattle in the West. The entertainment and atmosphere, however, are top notch (5/5). Keep your expectations at average for the food, but get ready for a real hootenanny the rest of the evening.
Typical timeline: arrive between 5:30 and 6:30, supper served at 7, entertainment from 7:45–9:30.

We chose this restaurant, as we were staying next door at the Motel 6 with our pups in tow and were craving Mexican food that would allow take out.  Now, I lived in San Diego for decades and currently live in Tucson AZ -- so we know great Mexican food both Baja and Sonoran influenced.  This place was pretty decent.  We ordered chips (and guacamole on a recommendation from the gal in the restaurant) and the guacamole was delicious.  The chips did not appear to be house made -- which was a bummer.  My husband had the carne asada and he liked it, came with beans and rice, as well as a stack of corn tortillas (store bought, lost a star).  I had the chimichanga which had diced up carne asada (or some type of beef) as they did not do ground or shredded.  It was interesting, as it did not appear to be in a flour tortilla, more of a puffed type dough.  I thought it was good -- no more no less.

We had a Mexican place picked out to try in Jackson, but when we got there, we found out they were closed for three days. We were still in the mood for Mexican, so we ended up here.

Covid-19: you can order and pay over the phone. You have to go inside to sign your receipt and pick up your food. The outside side walk area around the restaurant was very crowded too when we were waiting for our food to be ready.

We got the Twisted Cowgirl Dip, the Cheese Chile Relleno plate with green chile sauce, and the Wendell Special Quesadilla with shredded beef. They also served the takeout with chips and salsa which was nice.

Everything was ok, but not great. The Twisted Cowgirl Dip was my favorite of the bunch. Maybe it's because we had really amazing Mexican in Denver with the best green chile sauce, but it just didn't impress me. It wasn't bad, I just couldn't get excited about it.

Prices definitely felt inflated to me. Most plates were $16-$20. From what I've read, this seems similar to most places in Jackson.

I'd say I would try to find somewhere else when in Jackson, but I get the idea that slightly overpriced just ok food is what you find in Jackson.

@culvers Using midwest beef and dairy, I had a ButterBurger with cheese and cheese curds.

Every Culver’s cheese curd comes from La Grander Hillside Dairy in Stanley, Wisconsin. They were om nom all breaded with a blend of herbs and spices then deep fried. They were unnaturally delicious piled on my ButterBurger. What a treat. I am a Culver's curd nerd now.

The service was fast and friendly. Even though Culver's is 'fast food,' the quality is stupendous. Their menu has a wide variety of comfort food and there is even a drive thru.

It is a superb place to stop while in Cheyenne. I never knew there were three of these in the broader Denver Metro area. It's good to know.

Go for the cheese curds. You'll be glad you did.

If you're passing through Sundance on the 90, do yourself a favour - get off the interstate and go to Higbees.

Hotel is extremely outdated and staff needs to brush up on their customer service skills. The property probably hasn't had any sort of renovation since the 90's and it is long overdue. I was offered a package when I checked in which included a discount if I spent $30 in the gift shop/restaurant/gas station. I was told to bring back my receipts and they would apply the discount. The next morning I went into the front desk with my receipts only to be told I needed to turn them in the night before. I told the front desk attendant that I was not informed that it had to be turned in the same day I checked in, only to bring my receipts back and the front desk lady would take off the discount.  The front desk attendant rudely said,  "yeah her and she's not here". I then asked for a manager who quickly resolved the problem. If you're going to have a strict policy on how long customers have to turn in receipts for credits on a package I didn't even ask for then you need to inform the customers of that policy. Additionally, having a bad attitude with a customer who was obviously not informed correctly by your staff will not earn you business. I will NEVER stay here again!  Gross, outdated and rude staff!

Yum! Try the items in their Special Chinese and Chef Specialties section of the menu. The crispy spicy tofu and dry pot dishes (beef, shrimp, chicken wings, lamb) are super delicious and have authentic szechuan flavors! I grew up in parts of SE Asia where the Chinese food is amazing, so I'm thrilled to have some of these options available here in Jackson, it's a nice change from the typical Americanized Chinese fare. They also have the usual meal combos which include soup, appetizer and fried rice. But my husband and I went back twice in one week for their "Special Chinese" menu items. We went back again a couple of weeks later and ate inside this time, tried the Peking duck and typhoon short ribs which were also delicious! The typhoon short ribs are definitely best eaten in the restaurant when freshly cooked. Friendly staff, we'll definitely be back for more!

Today I ordered a 1/3lb never frozen USDA choice ground Angus chuck and brisket burger. Cheese: Ghost Pepper Jack. Toppings: lettuce, tomato, onion and pickle. As a side I ordered mashed potatoes with brown gravy.

The burger was absolutely delicious. The meat was cooked to perfection. WARNING! The Ghost Pepper Jack cheese has a kick. Delicious and spicy. The pickles used are noticeably delicious with a satisfying crunch. The one ingredient that can use improvement is the bun. It was a little dry, bland, and thicker than I would like. Overall amazing burger.

The mashed potatoes and brown gravy was really amazing. The country style mashed potatoes with the potato skins left on are one of my favorite styles of mashed potatoes. The gravy was as expected. Brings me back to my grandfather's homemade brown gravy.

Portion sizes were great and filling.

Prices are appropriate. I was actually impressed at the quality of food compared to the price. You definitely get your money's worth.

My waitress Dannika did an amazing job. She was friendly and welcoming. She was always quick to refill my soda when it was close to empty. She has a great positive attitude.

Thank you Hitching Post Restaurant and Saloon for an amazing meal and even better service.

Our large party came in late (9:30), but the staff made us feel welcome and right at home. Surrounded by tasteful British-colonization era decorations, complete with cricket bats and a water buffalo skull, we were whisked away to India and Southeast Asia. The upbeat music provided a wonderful tempo for the night.
We were delighted by the appetizers, each from a different culture but very well done. The Korean BBQ ribs were especially succulent; the accompanying kimchee perfectly sour and spicy.
Each of the entrees rocked. The butter curry was everyone's favorite, followed by the tiki masala and the pineapple fried rice. The general tso's chicken was too spicy for some in our crew, but I'm pretty sure they ate one of the peppers...I loved it. My one complaint was that the Bangkok street noodles, while they tasted authentic, smelled faintly of dog food, although I think I'm the only one in my party who smelled it.
Otherwise, it was a perfect place to end the evening. As one who has visited most mid level restaurants in Jackson, I'd put Teton Tiger as one of the best!

Perfection and wonderful service. Get the 10oz Bavette from Snake River Farms. Best steak ever consumed in my life. Also, received some profound steak-knowledge from the awesome bartender (ski-bro from Brooklyn - you are the man!). Cuts of steak with more marbling/fat, go with a medium, or slightly under that, to render the fat into the meat. (think of a middle ground between medium and medium-rare). Game-changer and it makes perfect sense. So many places and people just go with an attitude similar to  "ANYTHING MORE THAN MEDIUM RARE AND I'LL PUNCH YOU IN THE FACE AND ASK YOU TO LEAVE". I think we can leave that to the "well-done with a side of ketchup"-crew. When you learn a bit more about cows and the difference between cuts of meat you'll find yourself on a tastier, more knowledgeable bovine adventure.

The steak was so good that I came back the next night for the same meal and great service. The chef came out and I thanked him for the amazing food. Thank you thank you for a great experience! Can't wait to go back!

Trio was the best restaurant during our road trip from Arizona to Wyoming.  The food is not experimental, but simply classic flavors done right.  For appetizers we had the blue cheese waffle fries and BLT soup.  The soup had a fresh tomato flavor and was good, but those fries wow!  The fries were crispy outside but soft on the inside and the cheese sauce needs a soppin’ biscuit.  Creamy and not overpowering on the blue cheese, just the right mix.  Cocktails were the Martinez and the 1999, both were tasty.

Our main courses included the pork chop and the risotto with shrimp.  The risotto was good, but not great due to it being a little pasty rather than creamy. It came with an add-on option of shrimp or steak.  I definitely would go with the shrimp as it had a noticeable lemon flavor which pairs better with the shrimp.  This is my only negative of the meal.  I know you always run the risk ordering the pork chop but I am glad I stepped out on that ledge.  It was tomahawk style bone in and cooked to medium leaving it juicy.  Paired with the creamed corn gave it the right amount of sweetness that goes well with pork.  I recommend pairing it with their brown ale Mighty Bison, it added the right amount of nuttiness.

We finished off with the s’mores baked dessert in a cast iron pan. It was kind of like a graham cracker and fudge brownie cake topped with toasted marshmallow.  Delicious!  We decided to pair it with a glass of milk to satisfy the child inside.  Our waiter was excellent, sorry I do not remember his name.  4.5 out of 5 with the risotto preventing the perfect score.

My family has been coming here for generations, and it never disappoints. Trip after trip, we come and are consistently impressed by the quality of the pizza, not to mention the views! Sitting on the porch overlooking the Tetons and the Snake River, I'm not sure there's a more picturesque place in the world to eat a pizza.
The pizza has a wonderful crust, the sauce is bold, and the topping options are numerous. Our favorites were the Thor and the Static. The Greek and strawberry salads were delicious as well.
Pro-tip: come after it rains. If there's an afternoon thunderstorm in the forecast, it'll rain for a bit but it will clear up quickly, too. Offer to help dry off the tables and the servers will be very happy with you. It's just enough to push the crowds elsewhere and give you the solitude you seek.

SOOO DELICIOUS... and the servers are friendly and just generally awesome.

We had the Peruvian ceviche, a Morel Mushroom appetizer, Pork Belly masa appetizer, a beautiful Hamachi sushi beet appetizer, a seared sushi-grade Salmon steak, and panko breaded Idaho Trout. I had a fusion margarita that was so good that my normally suger-averse fiance "shared" it with me until I had to order a second one to "share".

For dessert, we ordered the mango Sticky rice panna cotta and the Chocolate creme pot (a dense mousse).

EVERYTHING was sooo good that we began reminiscing about Michelin-starred restaurants we'd been to in New York, San Francisco and Paris, haha... Hats off to the inventive and talented chef as well as our wonderful, kind and attentive server, Sara :)

Highly recommended to dine here if you are passing through Jackson Hole.

All of the staff were highly engaged and we had numerous people bringing us drinks, filling our waters and clearing away empty dishes throughout the dinner. A man who we assume was the general manager stopped by several times to make sure we were happy. We devoured every dish they brought us; it was all sooo tasty and beautifully presented.

An added bonus is that the Kitchen is located a couple blocks off the main drag in a quiet neighborhood with a subdued, contemporary decor, so it feels like a peaceful oasis after the barrage of (sometimes gaudy and often overwhelming) tourists traps you encounter downtown.

After doing my usual research this restaurant was on the list. Reservations highly recommend, but I did notice they were accepting walk ups with reasonable wait times considering CV19 (30-45 minutes). We were treated by a very friendly and knowledgeable waiter Siyad. He was an absolute pleasure to have. Knew the menu by heart and all sets for all plates. He accommodated changes after checking with the chef for a small up charge (veggie sub for the starch set). Started with the pork belly buns because, well, pork belly, doh! Great balance of heat and sweet with the rich braised pork belly. The bao bins could have been a little lighter and fluffier if I had any critique.

Next was the entrees. The wife had the pork shank that is braised and then deep fried. Crispy on the outside and creamy tender on the inside. Sticking with the starting bite, they balanced the dish with a wonderful carrot puree, crispy carrot chips, and pickled and fresh jalepenos. Fantastic dish! I had the Korean marinated wagyu beef with bone marrow fried rice. Just read that twice and just know it was everything you hoped for. Again, very well balanced with a nice "slaw" on top of the rice. Beef cooked perfect medium rare. Delicious!

We also had the house spicy margaritas with Jalepeno infused tequila and a touch of blackberry puree. Not to tart and most definitely not to sweet. Great cocktail! Best meal in Jackson this far! Cheers!
